1.10 Code Used to Scrape YouTube Comments¶

Below is the code forked from github used to parse the HTML and build out my own dataset.

A succinct explanation of the code flow:

get_random_links is the function used to obtain random YouTube links for analysis. I use a lexicon of the most used English words from a github repo. The words are randomly sampled, and then filtered down to less than 12 characters. Depending on the amount of links, find_instance_links is then used to query YouTube based on each random word, which in turn returns HTML source. The HTML source contains dozens of video links; the links are then extracted from the HTML source and one link is randomly selected from the search query.

Through each iteration of link, the scrape function is used. scrape calls the get_content function which uses a Selenium to open a clone web browser, load the HTML, then uses scroll to scroll for five minutes for each video, or until it fails to scroll at least failed_attempts times.

The HTML source, or resp is ultimately fed to an instance of CommentParser, where the video data is extracted, and the comments data is subsequently extracted using the VideoMetaData and CommentData classes.

# This is how I am pulling the data
class VideoMetadata:
    """Extract video meta data from BeautifulSoup parser object"""

    def __init__(self, parser):

        self.title = None
        self.desc = None
        self.publish_date = None
        self.author = None
        self.views = None
        self.likes = None
        self.dislikes = None

        self._get_video_metadata(parser)

    def _get_video_metadata(self, parser):
        """Searches the page for video metadata (uploaded, author, description, etc)"""

        self._parse_title(parser)
        self._parse_description(parser)
        self._parse_published(parser)
        self._parse_author(parser)
        self._parse_views(parser)
        self._parse_likes_dislikes(parser)

    def _parse_title(self, parser):
        """Prases the video Title"""
        title = parser.title
        if title:
            self.title = title.string.replace(" - YouTube", "")

    def _parse_description(self, parser):
        """Parses the video description"""
        description_block = parser.find("div", id="description")
        if description_block:
            self.desc = "\n".join(description_block.strings)

    def _parse_published(self, parser):
        """Parses the publish date"""
        date_block = parser.find("div", id="date")
        if date_block and date_block.text:
            date = date_block.text.replace("•", "")
            self.publish_date = date

    def _parse_author(self, parser):
        """Parses the author"""
        owner = parser.find("yt-formatted-string", class_="ytd-channel-name")
        if owner and owner.a and owner.a.string:
            self.author = owner.a.string

    def _parse_views(self, parser):
        """Parses the view count"""
        count_block = parser.find("span", class_="view-count")
        if count_block and count_block.string:
            count = count_block.string.replace(" views", "")
            self.views = count

    def _parse_likes_dislikes(self, parser):
        """Parse the likes and dislikes for the video"""
        views_block = parser.find_all(
            "yt-formatted-string", id="text", class_="ytd-toggle-button-renderer"
        )
        if views_block and views_block[0].get("aria-label"):
            likes = views_block[0]["aria-label"].replace(" likes", "").replace(" like", "")
            self.likes = likes

        if views_block and views_block[1].get("aria-label"):
            dislikes = views_block[1]["aria-label"].replace(" dislikes", "").replace(" dislike", "")
            self.dislikes = dislikes

    def to_json(self):
        """Returns all video metadata as a dictionary"""

        json = {
            "title": self.title,
            "description": self.desc,
            "published": self.publish_date,
            "channel": self.author,
            "views": self.views,
            "video_likes": self.likes,
            "video_dislikes": self.dislikes,
        }

        return json


def scrape(url):
    """Scrape youtube url for comments"""
    content = get_content(url)
    return content


def get_content(url, headless=True, pause=4):
    """Use selenium browser automation to open a youtube url, scroll to bottom and return the full page source"""
    # Configure selenium webdriver for Chrome and headless option if enabled
    options = webdriver.ChromeOptions()
    options.headless = headless
    driver = webdriver.Chrome(options=options, service_log_path=os.devnull)

    # Load URL, if url does not exist then selenium will crash out
    driver.get(url)

    print(f"Successfully loaded page: {url}")

    time.sleep(pause)

    # Youtube does not load all comments automatically and therefore we need to scroll to the bottom of the page.
    scroll(driver, failed_attempts=3)
    content = driver.page_source
    driver.close()
    return content


def scroll(driver, pause=2, delta=1000, failed_attempts=5):
    """
    Scroll to the bottom of the automated browser instance using webdriver.
    Depending on number of comments, this may take some time to scroll through to the bottom.
    inspired by https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47039874/scrape-dynamic-html-youtube-comments
    """

    print("Scrolling to bottom of page. This may take a while depending on number of comments.")

    # Try to see if window has a size (i.e not headless) otherwise we will stick with default
    height = driver.execute_script("return window.outerHeight")
    if height > 0:
        delta = height

    landed = 0
    target = delta

    failed = failed_attempts
    start = datetime.now()
    time_delta = 0

    while time_delta < 30:  # limit the scrolling to five minutes per video
        driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo({},{})".format(landed, target))
        time.sleep(pause)
        landed = driver.execute_script("return window.pageYOffset")

        # i.e haven't moved
        if landed < target:
            if failed == 0:
                print("Failed to scroll too many times! Breaking loop")
                break
            else:
                print("Failed to continue scrolling, trying again")
                failed -= 1
                print(f"Failed attempts: {failed}")
                continue
        else:
            failed = failed_attempts  # reset the failure counter

        target = landed + delta
        now = datetime.now()
        time_delta = (now - start).seconds

    print(f"Time elapsed: {time_delta} seconds")


class CommentData(object):
    def __init__(self, parser):
        self.author = None
        self.created = None
        self.comment = None
        self.likes = 0
        self.dislikes = 0
        self._get_content_data(parser)

    def _get_content_data(self, parser):
        """Searches the page for video metadata (uploaded, author, description, etc)"""

        self._parse_author(parser)
        self._parse_created(parser)
        self._parse_comment(parser)
        self._parse_likes_dislikes(parser)

    def _parse_author(self, parser):
        """Parse comment author as string"""

        author_block = parser.find("a", id="author-text")
        if author_block and author_block.span and author_block.span.string:
            author = author_block.span.string
            self.author = author.strip()

    def _parse_created(self, parser):
        """Parse comment create date"""
        header_block = parser.find("div", id="header-author")
        if header_block:
            created = header_block.find("yt-formatted-string").string
            self.created = created

    def _parse_comment(self, parser):
        """Prase comment itself and add to object"""
        comment_block = parser.find("yt-formatted-string", id="content-text")
        comment = ""

        if comment_block:
            for line in comment_block.strings:
                simple_line = line.replace("\n", " ")
                comment += simple_line.strip() + " "

            self.comment = comment

    def _parse_likes_dislikes(self, parser):
        """Parse comment likes, YouTube unfortunately doens't disclose comment dislikes"""
        views_block = parser.find("span", id="vote-count-middle")
        if views_block and views_block.get("aria-label"):
            likes = views_block["aria-label"].replace(" likes", "").replace(" like", "")
            self.likes = likes

    def to_json(self):
        """Return comment metadata as dictionary"""
        json = {
            "comment_author": self.author,
            "comment_created": self.created,
            "comment": self.comment,
            "comment_likes": self.likes,
            "comment_dislikes": self.dislikes,
        }

        return json


class CommentParser(object):
    """Parse comment data"""

    def __init__(self, source):
        parser = soup(source, "html5lib")  # load HTML source data as bs4 object
        self.video_metadata = VideoMetadata(parser)
        self.comments = []
        self._parse_comments(parser)

    def _parse_comments(self, parser):
        """Parse all of the comments on the page"""
        comment_blocks = parser.find_all("div", id="main", class_="ytd-comment-renderer")
        for blk in comment_blocks:
            comment = CommentData(blk)
            if comment.author is not None and comment.author != "":
                self.comments.append(comment)
        print(f"{len(self.comments)} comments extracted")

    def to_json(self):
        """Export all comments to nested dictionary"""
        json = []
        for c in self.comments:
            json.append(c.to_json())
        return json


# random YouTube URL code from https://stackoverflow.com/a/30965676
# Functions to find random youtube videos
def find_instance_links(word):
    """Query YouTube with randomly generated word, search for 'watch?v=...' in the HTML 
    source, and return a random link from the page source."""
    base_url = "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query="
    url = base_url + word
    print(f"Random search word: {word}")

    r = requests.get(url)
    text = r.text

    links = {}
    pos = 0
    while True:
        link, pos = find_watch(text, pos)  # find links in HTML source
        if link == None or pos == None:
            break
        pos += 1
        if ";" in link:
            continue
        links[link] = 1
    try:
        choice = random.choice(list(links.keys()))
    except IndexError:
        choice = None
    return choice


def find_watch(text, pos):
    """Return all instances in HTML source where "watch?v=" is mentioned"""
    start = text.find("watch?v=", pos)
    if start < 0:
        return None, None
    end = text.find(" ", start)
    if end < 0:
        return None, None

    if end - start > 200:  # silly heuristics, probably not a must
        return None, None

    return text[start : end - 1], start


def get_random_links(num_links=10):
    """Choose random words from 20k most used English words. Search YouTube with random words
    and extract random YouTube video links for scraping."""
    total_words = pd.read_csv("20k_most_used_words.txt", sep=" ", header=None)
    total_words.columns = ["word"]
    total_words = total_words["word"].to_list()
    random.shuffle(total_words)
    total_words = [
        w for w in total_words if 3 <= len(str(w)) <= 12
    ]  # limit the length of the words to not be verbose
    total_words = total_words[:num_links]  # limit amount of words to query for
    links = list()
    for i, word in zip(range(num_links), total_words):
        link = find_instance_links(word)
        if isinstance(link, str):
            link = link[:19]  # extract the right part of URL
            if len(link) == 19:
                links.append(link)
                print(f"Retrieved {link} from word: {word}, link number {i + 1}")
    return links

1.21 Data loading, comment language detection¶

The data is loaded via each indivdual .csv file saved over time, then concatenated to create a larger master data set master_df.

The like/dislike_ratio is then derived, using the following:

$$like\,dislike\,ratio = \frac{video\,likes}{video\,likes + video\,dislikes}$$

def convert_cols_to_numeric(master_df):
    """Use regex to parse extracted text data containing numeric values and convert to floats"""
    NUMERIC_COLS = ["comment_likes", "views", "video_dislikes", "video_likes"]

    master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].astype(str)

    for num_col in NUMERIC_COLS:
        master_df[num_col] = (
            master_df[num_col].str.extract(r"(\d{1,3}(?:[,]\d{3})*)", expand=False).fillna("")
        )
        master_df[num_col] = pd.to_numeric(master_df[num_col].str.replace(",", ""))

    return master_df


# Mahalanobis function taken from https://www.machinelearningplus.com/statistics/mahalanobis-distance/
def mahalanobis(x=None, data=None, cov=None):
    """Compute the Mahalanobis Distance between each row of x and the data  
    x    : vector or matrix of data with, say, p columns.
    data : ndarray of the distribution from which Mahalanobis distance of each observation of x is to be computed.
    cov  : covariance matrix (p x p) of the distribution. If None, will be computed from data.
    """
    x_minus_mu = x - np.mean(data)
    if not cov:
        cov = np.cov(data.values.T)
    inv_covmat = sp.linalg.inv(cov)
    left_term = np.dot(x_minus_mu, inv_covmat)
    mahal = np.dot(left_term, x_minus_mu.T)
    return mahal.diagonal()


def sentiment(comment, analyzer):
    "Return compound sentiment polarity scores using NLTK Sentiment Analyzer."
    score = analyzer.polarity_scores(comment)["compound"]
    return score


def detect_language(text):
    "Return language of text using langdetect."
    try:
        lang = detect(text)
    except:
        lang = None
    return lang

1.22 Prepare the comments for sentiment analysis¶

To clean the comments data (most all text cleaning methods use regular expressions), all @mentions and #hashtags are removed from comments. URLs are then removed, in addition to all punctuation. The comments are then all converted to lowercase. Emoticons such as =) express a positive sentiment, so emoticons/emojis need to be encoded as the closest text representations, so load_dict_smileys is used in addition to the emoji Python library to decode emojis like 👍 to :thumbs_up:.

Contractions are then converted to their respective expanded phrases, a small subset of stopwords are removed, references to video times (e.g. 4:59) are removed, and words are converted to their lemmas) using NLTK's WordNetLemmatizer.

In [15]:
# filter the data to only English comments
master_df = master_df.loc[master_df["comment_language"] == "en", :]

# remove any hashtags from the comments
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.replace(r"(@[A-Za-z0-9]+)|(#[A-Za-z0-9]+)", " ")

# remove any URLs
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.replace(r"(\w+:\/\/\S+)", " ")

# remove punctuation and replace them with spaces
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.replace(r"[\.\,\!\?\;\-\=]", " ")

# make everything lowercase
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.lower()

# replace smiley faces with words and replace contractions with full words
smileys = load_dict_smileys()
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.split()
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].swifter.apply(
    lambda x: [smileys[word] if word in smileys else word for word in x]
)

# make sure that contractions are all lowercase to match with tokens
contractions = load_dict_contractions()
contractions = {k.lower(): v for k, v in contractions.items()}
contractions = {k: v.lower() for k, v in contractions.items()}
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].swifter.apply(
    lambda x: [contractions[word] if word in contractions else word for word in x]
)

# remove small set of stopwords to maintain sentiment
stop_words = ["in", "of", "at", "a", "the"]
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].swifter.apply(
    lambda x: [word for word in x if word not in stop_words]
)

# convert emojis to their text representations
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.join(" ").swifter.apply(demojize)

# remove references to times in the videos, e.g. 4:15, 10:59
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.replace(r"[\d]{0,2}:[\d+]{0,2}", " ")

# remove colons and underscores from demoji, i.e. :laughing_face: to laughing face
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.replace(r"[\:]", " ")
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.replace(r"[\_]", " ")

# convert tokens to lemmas
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.split()
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].swifter.apply(
    lambda x: [lemmatizer.lemmatize(w) for w in x]
)

# join comments back to full form
master_df["comment"] = master_df["comment"].str.join(" ")

# calculate summary statistics grouped by video url
grouped = master_df.groupby("url")

sent_score_median = grouped.median()["sentiment_probs"]

max_sent_score = grouped.max()["sentiment_probs"]
min_sent_score = grouped.min()["sentiment_probs"]
comment_count = grouped.count()["comment"]

master_df = master_df.merge(sent_score_mean.rename("sent_score_mean"), how="left", on="url")
master_df = master_df.merge(sent_score_std.rename("sent_score_std"), how="left", on="url")

1.34 Can we find the most controversial videos without looking at likes and dislikes?¶
Below, the DataFrame is sampled to find videos with a comment sentiment range above 1.70, meaning they contain differing opinions. Additionally, videos with a very high coefficient of variation are selected; this measure is indicative of consistent differing opinions. Finally, the DataFrame is filtered further by looking for videos with median comment sentiment less than 0.15 to find high ratios of negative sentiment.


From these criteria, the DataFrame is then sampled to return videos with abnormally low like/dislike ratios. From the video titles, we can ascertain that their subject matter is somewhat controversial. For example, "Is Trump on the way out? - George Galloway" is centred around U.S. politics which is one of the most divisive topics in the world at the moment. The below sample is not a definitive method for finding controversial topics by any means, but a successful experiment to contextualize the relationship between comment sentiment and video likes/dislikes.

1.36 Outlier removal, correlation analysis, and modeling¶
Mahalanobis distance is then used to remove outliers in multidimensional space. The mahalanobis function was taken from here. A sample of the removed data is displayed; almost all of the videos sampled for removal have over 500 million views, which can be viewed as anomalies and should be excluded from results.


The video-level derived features are plotted in a correlation heatmap where it is observed that views are not related to like/dislike_ratio, video's sent_score_cv is not related to the like/dislike_ratio, but the sent_score_median of a video is related to the like/dislike_ratio with a Pearson's R value of 0.29.


To validate the significance of the correlation, an Ordinary Least Squares regression model is fit on the data with sent_score_median and sent_range as the features and like/dislike_ratio as the dependent variable.


    

  • The coefficients:
      

    • sent_score_median
      • 

    • sent_range
      • 

    

    • 



Are statistically significant as their p values are basically zero, meaning that we reject the null hypothesis that each coefficient is 0. The main result to internalise is the 0.29 correlation between median sentiment score and the likes/dislikes ratio, indicating there is a substantial (statistically significant) relationship between comment sentiment and the likes and dislikes on a video.

2.01 Obtain Video Level Data Over Time¶
The below script was executed every hour using a cronjob for about ~2,500 random YouTube videos that were different from the sentiment analysis sample. The script execution was ran over a two week period from 22 November to 7 December 2019.

def get_video_metadata(link):
    """Use pafy to pull video-level statistics as well as channel-level statistics for supplied link."""
    now = datetime.now()
    base_url = "https://www.youtube.com/"
    try:
        video = pafy.new(base_url + link)

    except:
        print(f"OSError at {link}")
        return None

    try:
        channel = pafy.get_channel(base_url + "user/" + video.username)

    except:
        try:
            channel = pafy.get_channel(base_url + "channel/" + video.username)
        except:
            channel = None

    try:
        channel_subscriptions = [
            {x.title: {"subscriber_count": int(x.subscriberCount)}} for x in channel.subscriptions
        ]

    except:
        channel_subscriptions = None

    output_payload = {
        "as_of": now.isoformat(),
        "title": video.title,
        "description": video.description,
        "url": video.watchv_url,
        "category": video.category,
        "likes": video.likes,
        "dislikes": video.dislikes,
        "keywords": video.keywords,
        "length": video.length,
        "username": video.username,
        "author": video.author,
        "viewcount": video.viewcount,
        "rating": video.rating,
        "published": video.published,
        "channel_description": channel.description if channel else None,
        "channel_subscriptions": channel_subscriptions,
        "subscriber_count": int(channel.subscriberCount) if channel else None,
        "channel_num_uploads": len(channel.uploads) if channel else None,
    }

    return output_payload


def process_pool(function, links):
    """Utilise multiprocessing to execute supplied function in parallel."""

    cores = mp.cpu_count() - 2  # leave overhead
    split_links = np.array_split(links, cores, axis=0)
    pool = Pool(cores)
    out = []
    for i, temp_res in enumerate(
        tqdm(pool.uimap(function, links), total=len(split_links), dynamic_ncols=True)
    ):
        out.append(temp_res)

    pool.close()
    pool.join()
    pool.clear()

    return out

2.12 Aggregation, feature creation, and cleaning¶
num_keywords is created as the number of keywords associated with a video; the same process is applied to channel_subscriptions to create num_subscriptions.


Clickbait titles are often all uppercase or make some outrageous claim. To attempt to measure this, pct_title_uppercase is created, which represents the number of uppercase characters as a percentage of all alphabetic characters in the title.


video_age is created as the timedelta in days between the as_of date (when the data was collected) amd the video's publish date. likes/views and dislikes/views are created to capture the engagement of viewers. Each measure indicates what proportion of the viewers of any given video choose to like or dislike.


view_growth is derived by dividing the viewcount feature by its time zero minimum value, thus normalising the viewcounts for comparison with other videos. Other growth figures are calculated as well.


channel_num_uploads_growth conveys how many videos the channel has uploaded since the data was initially collected. sub_growth is a normalized measure of how the subscriber base of the posting channel has developed over the sample period.













In [42]:



    


# convert date fields to datetime objects and creating additional features
df["as_of"] = pd.to_datetime(df["as_of"], infer_datetime_format=True, errors="coerce")
df["published"] = pd.to_datetime(df["published"], infer_datetime_format=True, errors="coerce")
df["viewcount"] = df["viewcount"].replace(
    0, 1
)  # this makes it so that we don't get infinity values when calculating growth
df["num_keywords"] = df["keywords"].apply(len)
df["num_subscriptions"] = df["channel_subscriptions"].apply(lambda x: len(x) if x else 0)

# percentage of uppercase characters in the title relative to all alphabetic characters
df["title"] = df["title"].astype(str)
df["pct_title_uppercase"] = df["title"].str.replace(" ", "").str.findall("([A-Z]+)").str.join(
    ""
).map(len) / df["title"].str.replace(" ", "").str.findall(r"([a-zA-Z]+)").str.join("").map(len)

# calculate the age of the videos relative to when the video was published
df["video_age"] = df["as_of"] - df["published"]
df["video_age"] = df["video_age"].dt.days

# add some features for analysis
df["likes/views"] = df["likes"] / df["viewcount"]
df["dislikes/views"] = df["dislikes"] / df["viewcount"]
df["like/dislike_ratio"] = df["likes"] / (
    df["likes"] + df["dislikes"]
)

df = df.sort_values(by="as_of")

# derive viewgrowth feature
view_count_min = df.groupby("url")["viewcount"].min()
view_count_min = view_count_min.reset_index().rename(columns={"viewcount": "viewcountmin"})
df = df.merge(view_count_min, how="left", on="url")
df["view_growth"] = df["viewcount"] / df["viewcountmin"]

# derive viewcount max feature
view_count_max = df.groupby("url")["viewcount"].max()
view_count_max = view_count_max.reset_index().rename(columns={"viewcount": "viewcountmax"})
df = df.merge(view_count_max, how="left", on="url")

# add viewgrowth max column
view_growth_max = df.groupby("url")["view_growth"].max()
view_growth_max = view_growth_max.reset_index().rename(columns={"view_growth": "view_growth_max"})
df = df.merge(view_growth_max, how="left", on="url")

# create feature displaying how the channel's uploaded videos have
# grown over the time the data was collected
video_uploaded_min = df.groupby("url")["channel_num_uploads"].min()
video_uploaded_min = video_uploaded_min.reset_index().rename(
    columns={"channel_num_uploads": "channel_num_uploads_min"}
)
df = df.merge(video_uploaded_min, how="left", on="url")
df["channel_num_uploads_growth"] = df["channel_num_uploads"] / df["channel_num_uploads_min"]

# derive subscribercount growth feature
sub_count_min = df.groupby("url")["subscriber_count"].min()
sub_count_min = sub_count_min.reset_index().rename(columns={"subscriber_count": "subcountmin"})
df = df.merge(sub_count_min, how="left", on="url")
df["sub_growth"] = df["subscriber_count"] / df["subcountmin"]

2.13 Additional feature creation: viewcount gradient/derivative with respect to time¶
A measure of interest is the rate at which a video grows, and how that growth rate changes over time. In order to do analyse this effectively, the gradient of the normalised viewcount view_growth column is taken with respect to time.













In [44]:



    


output = StringIO()
csv_writer = writer(output)

for url in tqdm(
    df.loc[:, "url"].unique()
):  # iterate through every url, filtering the DataFrame each time
    url_df = df.loc[df["url"] == url, :]
    url_df = url_df.sort_index(ascending=True)  # ensure it is sorted correctly
    tmp = pd.Series(
        url_df["view_growth"].values, url_df["as_of"].values
    )  # create temporary series of just view growtth and date
    tmp.index = pd.to_datetime(tmp.index)  # set the index to be  datetime values
    tmp_ = tmp.resample(
        "h"
    ).ffill()  # interpolate the time axis to make it equal for calculating the gradients of growth rates
    viewcount_slope = pd.Series(
        np.gradient(tmp_.values), tmp_.index, name="viewcount_slope"
    )  # calculate the gradient
    url_df.index = url_df["as_of"]
    url_df = url_df.sort_index()
    tmp = pd.concat([tmp_.rename("values"), viewcount_slope], axis=1)
    url_df = pd.merge_asof(
        url_df, tmp, left_index=True, right_index=True
    )  # merge back with original dataframe on closest time index after interpolation
    for i, row in url_df.iterrows():
        csv_writer.writerow(
            row
        )  # write each row of the url_df to a csv object in memory for efficiency

output.seek(0)  # point to the beginning of the StringIO object
result = pd.read_csv(output)
result.columns = list(df.columns) + [
    "values",
    "viewcount_slope",
]  # reset the columns as they are removed in the process of StringIO writing
result["as_of"] = pd.to_datetime(result["as_of"])
result["published"] = pd.to_datetime(result["published"])

2.33 Plot video characteristics for all videos published in the last 3 years; observations¶
Now looking at all videos, not just the viral videos, there are more insightful observations. The correlation map includes approximately 1500 videos published in the last 3 years for recency's sake. The amount of likes and dislikes are very correlated with the viewcount of any video. Videos with the category Music have the highest positive correlation with viewcount, meaning that music videos get the most views.


With respect to the like/dislike_ratio feature, it is not surprising that videos with the News & Politics category have a negative correlation.


More formal, academic videos like those with the categories Science & Technology, or News & Politics have negative correlations with the percentage uppercase in the title, whereas Gaming videos have a positive correlation, implying that gaming videos have more clickbait titles. Interestingly enough, pct_title_uppercase is also positively correlated with the likes/views ratio, meaning that viewers like a video more when the title is all uppercase. This also may be due to the fact that YouTubers that post all uppercase gaming videos also most likely ask their viewers to like their videos explicitly.


Of the videos in the 3 year sample, videos that are older tend to have a lower likes/view ratio; this may be due likes becoming more and more important on the YouTube platform in recent years.


Channels that post News & Politics videos tend to have the most videos on their channels, with those that upload Sports content also showing a positive correlation.
